        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "The problem stems form starting an `autocmd`, not the `*`. For example:\r\n```\r\nexport VIMINIT =\"\r\nautocmd VimResized cpp :wincmd =\r\nset number\r\n\"\r\n```\r\nWould exhibit the same issue.\r\n\r\n> However when I use an multi-line example without a `*` it does seem to work:\r\n\r\nMultiline commands get interpreted as one giant command with the lines separated by a `|`, so that example would become:\r\n```\r\nset number | set hlsearch | set incsearch | set lazyredraw  | set ruler | set autowrite | set autoread | set spelllang=en | noremap <silent> k gk | noremap <silent> j gj | set spellsuggest=8 | noremap <silent> 0 g0 | noremap <silent> $ g$ | onoremap <silent> j gj | onoremap <silent> k gk\r\n```\r\nWhich also works.\r\n\r\n> And is there something like ; to denote end of command in vimscript?\r\n\r\nNot really, the closest you can get is chaining commands with `|`, but it doesn't work with every command. Unfortunately, `autocmd` is one of the commands it doesn't work with. See`:help :bar` for more information.\r\n\r\nAs a super hacky work around you can do something like:\r\n```\r\nexport VIMINIT='\r\nexecute \"autocmd VimResized * :wincmd =\"\r\nset number\r\n'\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo avoid starting an autocmd. That should work.\r\n",
